You&#x27;re assuming that NULL represents an error. It doesn&#x27;t, it represents the lack of a value.<p><pre><code>    Widget w = {};
    widget_init(&w);
    widget_debug_print(&w);

    void widget_debug_print(Widget* widget) {
        printf(&quot;title: &#x27;%s&#x27;
&quot;, widget->title);
        printf(&quot;size: (%d, %d)
&quot;, widget->w, widget->h);
    }
</code></pre>
I don&#x27;t know what widget_init() does. It turns out that widget->title is NULL. Great! Now I know.<p>You&#x27;re basically saying: &quot;In an ideal world, that printf() would be enclosed in an if (), then the code is compliant&quot;.<p>OK, but who&#x27;s going to fix it? The vendor went bankrupt years ago, the code only exits on JAZ tapes, the whole of Uzbekistan relies on it, etc...<p>Relevant: <a href="https://lkml.org/lkml/2012/12/23/75" rel="nofollow">https://lkml.org/lkml/2012/12/23/75</a>
